# WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia

Jump to: navigation, search

The **WrestleMania Women 's Battle Royal**[1] is a [professional
wrestling](/wiki/Professional_wrestling "Professional wrestling") [battle
royal](/wiki/Professional_wrestling_battle_royal "Professional wrestling
battle royal") held at [WrestleMania](/wiki/WrestleMania "WrestleMania") by
[American](/wiki/United_States "United States") [professional wrestling
promotion](/wiki/Professional_wrestling_promotion "Professional wrestling
promotion") [WWE](/wiki/WWE "WWE"). The inaugural battle royal was held during
the [WrestleMania 34](/wiki/WrestleMania_34 "WrestleMania 34") pre-show. The
winner of the match receives the WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal Trophy.

The match was originally named **The Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal**
in honor of [The Fabulous Moolah](/wiki/The_Fabulous_Moolah "The Fabulous
Moolah") – a [WWE Hall of Famer](/wiki/WWE_Hall_of_Fame "WWE Hall of Fame")
billed as a pioneer of women's wrestling. However, her name was removed from
the match after backlash from fans due to the controversy surrounding Moolah's
past.

This is the female counterpart to the [André the Giant Memorial Battle
Royal](/wiki/Andr%C3%A9_the_Giant_Memorial_Battle_Royal "André the Giant
Memorial Battle Royal"), which was introduced at [WrestleMania
XXX](/wiki/WrestleMania_XXX "WrestleMania XXX").[2]

##
History[[edit](/w/index.php?title=WrestleMania_Women%27s_Battle_Royal&action=edit&section=1
"Edit section: History")]

On the March 12, 2018, episode of _[Raw](/wiki/WWE_Raw "WWE Raw")_ , WWE
established The Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal in honor of Moolah, and
that the first match would take place at [WrestleMania
34](/wiki/WrestleMania_34 "WrestleMania 34") on April 8, with the winner
receiving The Fabulous Moolah Memorial Trophy (made in the likeness of
Moolah).[3][4] After a controversy over their decision to honor Moolah, WWE
changed the name to the "WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal".[1] The trophy was
subsequently renamed, and redesigned as a simple golden cup with tassels atop
the trophy's base.[5] The inaugural match was won by
[Naomi](/wiki/Naomi_\(wrestler\) "Naomi \(wrestler\)"), after she last
eliminated [Bayley](/wiki/Bayley_\(wrestler\) "Bayley \(wrestler\)").

## Name
controversy[[edit](/w/index.php?title=WrestleMania_Women%27s_Battle_Royal&action=edit&section=3
"Edit section: Name controversy")]

Main article: [The Fabulous Moolah § Allegations of
exploitation](/wiki/The_Fabulous_Moolah#Allegations_of_exploitation "The
Fabulous Moolah")

[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/77/The_Fabulous_Moolah_circa_date_photograph.jpg/170px-
The_Fabulous_Moolah_circa_date_photograph.jpg)](/wiki/File:The_Fabulous_Moolah_circa_date_photograph.jpg)

[](/wiki/File:The_Fabulous_Moolah_circa_date_photograph.jpg "Enlarge")

[The Fabulous Moolah](/wiki/The_Fabulous_Moolah "The Fabulous Moolah"), c.
2003

The decision to hold a battle royal in honor of The Fabulous Moolah drew fan
rage.[6][7] Tufayel Ahmed of _[Newsweek](/wiki/Newsweek "Newsweek")_ wrote
that Moolah "isn't quite the bastion of female empowerment she is proclaimed
to be", with "years of allegations" that she had "monopolized women’s
wrestling in North America", taken a large percentage of other wrestlers' pay,
and "sexually exploited women under her mentorship".[8] Jason Powell, from
_Pro Wrestling Dot Net_ , criticized the tribute as it does not "exactly mesh
with what WWE wants their women's division push to represent".[9] David
Bixenspan of _[Deadspin](/wiki/Deadspin "Deadspin")_ pointed out that given
Moolah's alleged abuses, fans were particularly turned off by WWE personnel
describing Moolah as a "trailblazer for women’s equality". WWE also promoted
Moolah as having "challenged the gender norms of a once male-dominated sport",
but Bixenspan described that Moolah, by wrestling and teaching her students an
"in-ring style low on athleticism and heavy on hair-pulling", relegated
women's wrestling to "much more of a sideshow" instead of a "legitimate
headline attraction" in the previous era.[10] [Mad Maxine](/wiki/Mad_Maxine
"Mad Maxine"), a wrestler trained by Moolah, commented that Moolah was the
most "monstrous" person she had ever met, and that wrestling is "about
generating heat. And you can't draw more heat than naming a match for The
Fabulous Moolah."[11]

On March 12, a [Change.org](/wiki/Change.org "Change.org") petition appeared
online demanding WWE change the name of its upcoming Fabulous Moolah Memorial
Battle Royal, nearing its 10,000 signature goal.[7][12] Initially, WWE reacted
by disabling the comments section of their YouTube video that announced the
Moolah battle royal.[13][14] Later, [Snickers](/wiki/Snickers "Snickers"), the
primary sponsor of WrestleMania 34, called the decision to honor Moolah
"unacceptable" and said they were "engaging with the WWE to express our
disappointment."[15] On March 14, WWE renamed the match "WrestleMania Women's
Battle Royal", removing Moolah's name from the event.[7][1]
